    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.0"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">0</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Camdenton, Mo.
                        Oct. 1, 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John Streker</addrLine>
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">K.O.M.U. - T.V.</hi></addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">EPIC AMERICA</hi>
                
                    <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you for the program "Epic America" which is my time for relaxation. Nothing could relax me more than listening to the gentleman who reads the story. He is wonderful. That half-hour is not near enough time for such enjoyment.</p>
                
                <p>Day-dreaming, looking back I think of another elderly gentleman who could read like that (and few can), his name was Professor Chisholm and he was the idol of the community. This was in Michigan and I was a girl, just fifteen. It seems a century ago.</p>
                
                <p><hi rend="caps">PLEASE</hi> keep this gentleman 'on the air' for a long, long time. "Evangeline" was my favorite story and I would sure like to hear this gentleman read that story, it would be "out of this world" as my son would say.</p>
                
                <p>This half-hour is really something to look forward to and busy or not - I'll be listening. Thank you again.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Elsa M. Sulin</signed>
                    ______________________________
                    <signed>Mrs. Edw. G. Sulin</signed>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Buffalo Star Route</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Camdenton, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p>And thanks John for your sweet smile, we are still watching for it - as we did from the beginning, before you came to this station, remember? One of my grandchildren who visited here this summer from <hi rend="caps">W.</hi>Va. said "He has a smile that is as radiant as the sun." She is just seven, so you see she agrees with grandmother.</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
